<DOC><DOCNO> AP890410-0107 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2059EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NewsroomTampering     04-10 0188</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Newsroom Tampering,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Former News Director Charged In Computer-Tampering Case</HEAD><DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former news editor at WTSP-Channel 10 wascharged Monday with scheming with a colleague to tap into theconfidential computer system of a competing television station.   Terry Cole, 32, surrendered at the Hillsborough State Attorney'soffice on a conspiracy charge and two counts of computer-relatedcrimes, said Sam Jones, head of the Florida Department of LawEnforcement in Tampa.   Cole was fired in March, along with Michael I. Shapiro, 33,assistant news director at the ABC affiliate.   Shapiro was charged with 14 counts of computer-related crimes inan alleged series of raids on the computer news files of Channel13, the CBS affiliate. He has been released on his own recognizanceand hasn't come to trial yet.   When Shapiro was arrested Feb. 7, investigators said they had noinformation that anyone else was involved, but since have obtainedevidence that ``Terry Cole took part, had full knowledge, gave hisblessings,'' Jones said Monday.   Shapiro is a former assignment manager at Channel 13 where hehelped set up security for the computer system.</TEXT></DOC>